Navigation
==========

Easily define navigations in your controllers, and render navigation items in your views.


Basic Example
=============

In your controller:

	class PagesController < ApplicationController
		navigation :main_menu, :pages
	end

	class PostsController < ApplicationController
  	navigation :main_menu, :posts
	end
	
In your view:

  <% navigate :main_menu, :pages do %>
    <%= link_to 'Pages', pages_path %>
  <% end %>

  <% navigate :main_menu, :posts do %>
  	<%= link_to 'Users', users_path %>
  <% end %>

Assuming the request routed to the PagesController, the view will
render as:

	<span class="navigation_item selected">
		<a href="/pages">Pages</a>
	</span>
	
	<span class="navigation_item">
		<a href="/posts">Posts</a>
	</span>
	

Navigate Independently
======================

Controller actions can navigate independently of one another:

	class PostsController
		navigation :post_menu, :show, :only => :show
		navigation :post_menu, :edit, :only => :edit
	end
	

Conditional Rendering
=====================

In your view, you can choose when to render a navigation item using
the :if option:
	
	<% navigate :main_menu, :users, :if => administrator? do %>
	  ...
	<% end %>
	
	
Customize Navigation Items
==========================

HTML Tag
--------
You can specify a different HTML tag for your navigation items using
the :tag option:

	<% navigate :main_menu, :pages, :tag => :li do %>
		...
	<% end %>
	
Will render as:

	<li class="navigation_item">
		...
	</li>

CSS Class
---------
You can specify css class names using the :class option:

  <% navigate :main_menu, :pages, :class => 'blue' do %>
  	...
  <% end %>

Will render as:

	<span class="blue navigation_item">
		...
	</span>


